## Fetching and caching safety
- Assume users may run old bundles after deploy; tolerate API responses that are backward compatible during rollout windows.
- Prefer cache keys and invalidation strategies that stay correct when entities change (optimistic updates must reconcile with server truth).
- Avoid destructive local state updates without a clear rollback path on failure.

## Backward compatibility
- New UI code should tolerate older API responses during phased backend rollouts when applicable.
- Coordinate breaking API changes across repositories; do not assume atomic backend and frontend deploys unless guaranteed.

## Large lists and heavy views
- Be deliberate about virtualization, pagination, and incremental loading for large datasets.
- Measure before optimizing; avoid premature micro-optimizations.

## Bundle and runtime performance
- Keep bundle size intentional; lazy-load routes and heavy dependencies where it helps real user journeys.
- Avoid blocking the main thread with large synchronous work; chunk or defer where appropriate.

## Connection usage
- Reuse HTTP connections via the browser and client defaults; avoid redundant parallel duplicate requests for the same resource without deduplication.
